          I will never forget Group B cars. The sound the Audis and Lancias made is still ringing in my ears since the first time i saw one in Acropolis.
          Spectators in Greece were relatively ok if you compare them with the Portoguese.
          Carlos Sainz once said that the worst moment he had with spectators was in Portogal when he got to the service area and they found 2 fingers stuck on the bonnet. Spectators were actually trying to touch the car as it drove by.


          Here are some vids:



          Listen to the crew....


          Even the police are nuts as spectators:


          Here is what happens when the driver loses it in this places:







          I have had countless arguments with stupid spectators in this events.
          Mainly with dumb folks that do not realize its not safe to sit on the outside of a corner!!!
          Here is one that i actually witnessed and unfortunately a boy and his father lost their lives.



          The sad thing in these cases is that the drivers get the blame and even if they dont they live with the guilt.
          I still dont realize how people can risk both their lives and the competitors lives by being so stupid! Its sad when there is a loss like that but it makes you wonder what goes through the mind of these people.
          Specially since they are constantly told by others not to stand so close/or on those spots



          On a brighter note.... here is a friend of mines Group B monster he recently bought in Greece!!!! This thing is nuts!!!!!

                            Spanish driver Antonio Zanini giving the Talbot Sunbeam Lotus one last WRC fling, and the crowds one last thrill, taking 6th overall on the 1983 Rally of Portugal, probably the car's last points finish. Looks like the co driver has found time to wave at the photographer!
